INSERT INTO blog_posts (title, slug, excerpt, content, category_id, image_url, published, published_at)
VALUES (
  'The Surrey Assignment Flip: How to Sell Your Presale Contract Before Completion',
  'surrey-presale-assignment-flip-how-to-sell-contract',
  'Bought a presale in Surrey and need to exit? Uzair breaks down exactly how to execute an assignment sale — developer lifting clauses, fee negotiation, MLS restrictions, CRA tax rules, and how to walk away with a profit.',
  E'You bought a presale condo in Surrey two years ago. The building is almost finished, but your life has changed. Maybe you got a new job, maybe interest rates shifted, or maybe you just want to take your equity and walk away.\n\nYou are probably asking: Can I sell my presale condo before it''s finished? What exactly is an assignment sale in BC? And how much does a developer charge for an assignment fee?\n\nI am Uzair Muhammad, and I specialize in exit strategies. Most retail buyers don''t even know they have an eject button built into their contract. This guide breaks down the mechanics of a Surrey assignment flip, the risks involved, and how to execute a profitable exit before you ever have to take out a mortgage.\n\n## The Reality of the Assignment Flip\n\nAn assignment sale is not the sale of a physical condo; it is the sale of your *contract*. You are transferring your right to purchase the unit to a new buyer.\n\nHere is how the math works: If you secured a Surrey presale at $500,000 with a $50,000 deposit, and the market value is now $600,000, you can "assign" the contract. The new buyer pays you your original $50,000 deposit, plus the $100,000 in equity lift, minus fees. You walk away with a massive return on your initial cash, and you never had to qualify for a mortgage or pay closing costs.\n\n> But it is not a free-for-all. Developers control the board. They do not want your assignment sale competing with their remaining unsold inventory, so they put strict "lifting clauses" in your contract that dictate exactly when and how you can sell.\n\n## Why This Matters for Your Capital\n\nIf you are an investor, the assignment flip is often the primary goal. But if you don''t understand the developer''s assignment fees, your profit margin will disappear. Some developers charge a flat fee of $1,500; others charge 2% to 3% of the original purchase price. If you don''t negotiate this fee *before* you sign the original contract, you are at their mercy.\n\nIf you are a first-time buyer who suddenly needs to exit the contract because you can no longer qualify for the mortgage, an assignment sale is your lifeline. But if you are forced to sell in a down market, you might have to assign the contract for less than you paid, meaning you lose a portion of your deposit.\n\n> The Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) heavily scrutinizes assignment sales. If your primary intent was to flip the contract for profit, the gains are taxed as business income, not capital gains.\n\n## How to Execute a Profitable Exit\n\nHere is the exact framework for navigating a Surrey assignment sale:\n\n1. **Check the Lifting Clauses:** Can I sell my presale condo before it''s finished? Only if the developer allows it. Read your contract. Some developers ban assignments entirely until the building is 90% sold out.\n\n2. **Calculate the Assignment Fee:** How much does a developer charge for an assignment fee? It varies wildly. I always negotiate this fee down or have it waived completely during the initial purchase phase. If you didn''t, you need to factor this cost into your asking price.\n\n3. **Navigate the Marketing Restrictions:** You cannot list an assignment on the public MLS without the developer''s written permission, which they rarely give. You need a realtor with an exclusive, private network of buyers to execute the sale quietly.\n\n4. **Prepare for Taxes:** Consult an accountant immediately. Understand the implications of the CRA''s business income rules and BC''s home flipping tax before you agree to a sale price.\n\n## The Bottom Line\n\nAn assignment sale is your eject button, but it requires precise timing, a deep understanding of developer contracts, and a private buyer network. If you try to execute a flip without knowing the rules, your capital will get trapped.\n\n> Stop guessing your exit strategy. Build the plan before you sign the contract, not after.\n\n## Work With a Presale Specialist\n\nStop guessing your exit strategy. I am Uzair Muhammad, and I build calculated exit plans for my clients before they ever sign a contract. I negotiate the assignment fees upfront and leverage my private network to execute quiet, profitable flips in Surrey. Book a free strategy call with me today at presalewithuzair.com, and let''s map out your next move.',
